      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Shell Foundations for Azure CLI Scripts"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Before writing a single az command, the script header determines how errors propagate. Without strict options, a failed CLI command is silently ignored and the script continues into an inconsistent state."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Essential set Flags"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# These three lines protect every script that follows:\nset -e          # Exit immediately if any command returns non-zero\nset -u          # Treat unset variables as errors\nset -o pipefail # A pipe fails if any command in the pipe fails\nIFS=$'\\n\\t'    # Safer word splitting: only newlines and tabs, not spaces\n\n# Combined short form:\nset -euo pipefail"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Without set -e, az commands that fail silently continue execution. Without set -o pipefail, az vm list | grep something exits 0 even when az vm list fails."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
