      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "For greenfield scripts: use az show || az create guards for 1-5 resources, ARM/Bicep for anything larger. Never write scripts that assume resources don't exist \u2014 always check first."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Effective Azure CLI scripting rests on five principles: fail-fast shell options (set -euo pipefail), idempotent create-or-skip guards, output captured via -o tsv or -o json rather than parsed table text, structured environment-variable interfaces, and EXIT trap\u2013based cleanup for partial failure rollback. These patterns make scripts safe to run repeatedly from CI/CD pipelines, operationally correct under transient network failures, and easy to test in isolation by overriding environment variables."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
